A new paper shows that less than 2 months of exposure to Twitter’s algorithmic feed significantly shifts people’s political views to the right. 

Moving from chronological feed to the algorithmic feed also increases engagement. 

This is one of the most concerning papers I’ve read in awhile.

The political effects of X's feed algorithm
https://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-026-10098-2
Received: 16 December 2024
Accepted: 4 January 2026
Published online: 18 February 2026
Open access
• Check for updates
Germain Gauthier,5, Roland Hodler?5, Philine Widmer35 & Ekaterina Zhuravskaya3,4,5 m
Feed algorithms are widely suspected to influence political attitudes. However, previous evidence from switching off the algorithm on Meta platforms found no political effects'. Here we present results from a 2023 field experiment on Elon Musk's platform X shedding light on this puzzle. We assigned active US-based users randomly to either an algorithmic or a chronological feed for 7 weeks, measuring political attitudes and online behaviour. Switching from a chronological to an algorithmic feed increased engagement and shifted political opinion towards more conservative positions, particularly regarding policy priorities, perceptions of criminal investigations into Donald Trump and views on the war in Ukraine. In contrast, switching from the algorithmic to the chronological feed had no comparable effects.
Neither switching the algorithm on nor switching it off significantly affected affective polarization or self-reported partisanship. To investigate the mechanism, we analysed users' feed content and behaviour. We found that the algorithm promotes conservative content and demotes posts by traditional media. Exposure to algorithmic content leads users to follow conservative political activist accounts, which they continue to follow even after switching off the algorithm, helping explain the asymmetry in effects. These results suggest that initial exposure to X's algorithm has persistent effects on users' current political attitudes and account-following behaviour, even in the absence of a detectable effect on partisanship.

Der Verlag B-Love Manga bringt den Spin-off »Tsugai Miman no Bokura wa Kitto« von Licca Arata (Mein Partner ist ein Vollblut-Omega) nach Deutschland. Der Einzelband erscheint nach aktueller Planung voraussichtlich im Mai 2026. Neben der regulären Ausgabe erscheint auch eine Limited Edition mit spicy Booklet, zwei Acryl Keychains, Coververedelung sowie einem limitierten Artprint, exklusiv im Webshop.

In Japan liefen die einzelnen Kapitel von August 2023 bis September 2024 auf der Webplattform »G-Lish« des japanischen Verlag Julian Publishing und wurde zu einem Einzelband zusammengefasst. 

📜 Beschreibung (B-Love Manga)》
Natsume Oga ist ein aufstrebender Schauspieler und steht ständig im Rampenlicht. Doch was niemand wissen darf: Er ist ein Omega. In einer Branche, die Perfektion verlangt und keine Schwäche duldet, kostet ihn das mehr, als er zugeben will, besonders in Momenten körperlicher und seelischer Überforderung.

Rückhalt findet Natsume bei Kotaro Chitose, einem warmherzigen Beta und seinem langjährigen Weggefährten. Zwischen Drehs, Hitzephasen und unter den neugierigen Blicken der Öffentlichkeit wächst aus ihrer Freundschaft langsam mehr. Aber hat eine Liebe zwischen Beta und Omega überhaupt eine Chance, wenn eine Paarbindung ausgeschlossen ist?

Vorhang auf für eine Geschichte, die nicht dem Omegaverse-Drehbuch folgt.

external.title: Courts have generally ruled that the Fourth Amendment protection against compelled disclosure of passwords does not apply to biometric authentication, such as facial recognition or fingerprint scanning, meaning authorities can compel individuals to unlock their phones with their biometrics in some cases. This vulnerability is not limited to journalists and activists, as anyone can be exposed to unauthorized access to their phone and data through forced biometric unlocks, including instances of domestic abuse or theft. To mitigate this risk, users can permanently disable biometric authentication on their smartphones, requiring a passcode to unlock the device, or temporarily deactivate the feature by restarting their phone, which will require a passcode to be entered before biometric authentication can be used again. On iPhones, biometric authentication can be disabled by opening the Settings app, tapping “Face/Touch ID and Passcode,” and toggling the “iPhone Unlock” switch to “off,” while Android users can disable the feature through the Settings app, with the exact steps varying depending on the phone model.
